1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,645
In this worksheet, I'm going to look at how to use shape

2
00:00:03,645 --> 00:00:07,935
or size to encode a third variable in scatter plots.

3
00:00:07,935 --> 00:00:12,840
We're going to start by importing the libraries for

4
00:00:12,840 --> 00:00:19,095
both data analysis and visualization and also the fuel economy dataset.

5
00:00:19,095 --> 00:00:22,820
We will also be extracting transmission type,

6
00:00:22,820 --> 00:00:26,915
looking at automatic and manual vehicles.

7
00:00:26,915 --> 00:00:29,840
Now, we have too much data to plot.

8
00:00:29,840 --> 00:00:31,985
To reduce over plotting,

9
00:00:31,985 --> 00:00:35,630
we're going to take a random subset of 200 cars.

10
00:00:35,630 --> 00:00:38,390
Then we're going to combine that with a small amount of

11
00:00:38,390 --> 00:00:42,830
horizontal jitter to ensure plotting markers don't overlap.

12
00:00:42,830 --> 00:00:47,570
To do this, we're going to use Numpy's random library,

13
00:00:47,570 --> 00:00:53,225
where we randomly select 200 rows without replacement.

14
00:00:53,225 --> 00:00:55,970
Here you see our new DataFrame,

15
00:00:55,970 --> 00:01:00,750
df_subset only has 200 rows.

16
00:01:00,750 --> 00:01:07,940
Recall that both the reg plot and scatter functions do have a marker parameter.

17
00:01:07,940 --> 00:01:14,405
However, this specifies the specific marker to use and it only takes a string.

18
00:01:14,405 --> 00:01:18,185
If we were to look at, let's just say,

19
00:01:18,185 --> 00:01:22,845
automatic transmission from our df_subset and

20
00:01:22,845 --> 00:01:28,790
recreate a regression plot where our x-variable is engine displacement.

21
00:01:28,790 --> 00:01:32,170
The y-variable is combined efficiency.

22
00:01:32,170 --> 00:01:35,720
We're going to add a little bit of x jitter to make it easier to

23
00:01:35,720 --> 00:01:40,925
read and we're also not going to plot our regression line.

24
00:01:40,925 --> 00:01:43,630
We end up with something like this.

25
00:01:43,630 --> 00:01:49,435
For marker, I selected an upward pointing carrot or triangle.

26
00:01:49,435 --> 00:01:53,840
However, we want to plot both automatic and manual.

27
00:01:53,840 --> 00:01:58,855
In order to do this, we set up a list of lists called T-type.

28
00:01:58,855 --> 00:02:01,430
In this list of lists,

29
00:02:01,430 --> 00:02:06,575
we have the category or the class category,

30
00:02:06,575 --> 00:02:11,525
automatic or manual, and then also the marker we want to use.

31
00:02:11,525 --> 00:02:14,705
We then loop over this list of lists.

32
00:02:14,705 --> 00:02:23,360
Here we plot our reg plot for just that one list of data.

33
00:02:23,360 --> 00:02:30,270
We plot here for our reg plot only one list at a time.

34
00:02:30,340 --> 00:02:33,755
Note that because we sampled our DataFrame,

35
00:02:33,755 --> 00:02:36,785
your plot might look slightly different than mine,

36
00:02:36,785 --> 00:02:39,400
but should show similar trends.

37
00:02:39,400 --> 00:02:46,055
It's worth noting that because we plotted reg plot multiple times,

38
00:02:46,055 --> 00:02:52,150
Seaborn knew to plot each one with its own unique color.

39
00:02:52,150 --> 00:02:58,670
This is fortunate since the two transmission types have quite a good deal of overlap.

40
00:02:58,670 --> 00:03:03,655
For the legend, we use Matplotlib's legend function.

41
00:03:03,655 --> 00:03:05,795
As an argument to this function,

42
00:03:05,795 --> 00:03:11,480
we give a list of labels to place on the legend one for each reg plot call.

43
00:03:11,480 --> 00:03:13,775
Now, instead of transmission type,

44
00:03:13,775 --> 00:03:18,230
what happens if we wanted to add carbon dioxide emissions as a third variable?

45
00:03:18,230 --> 00:03:20,725
Since CO_2 is numeric,

46
00:03:20,725 --> 00:03:24,095
one encoding we could use is marker size.

47
00:03:24,095 --> 00:03:29,300
The goal would be higher CO_2 emissions would result in larger markers.

48
00:03:29,300 --> 00:03:35,390
Matplotlib's scatter function, we can set marker size with the S parameter,

49
00:03:35,390 --> 00:03:39,590
setting it to the name of the column we want to map it to, CO_2.

50
00:03:39,590 --> 00:03:45,995
Reg plot, we set the parameter as part of a dictionary on scatter keyword arguments.

51
00:03:45,995 --> 00:03:49,780
Here, we're going to divide the values by two.

52
00:03:49,780 --> 00:03:52,140
The trend seems pretty clear to me.

53
00:03:52,140 --> 00:03:55,250
It seems that as engine size increases,

54
00:03:55,250 --> 00:03:57,800
the circles tend to be a little bit larger,

55
00:03:57,800 --> 00:04:02,005
meaning that CO_2 emissions increase.

56
00:04:02,005 --> 00:04:05,295
But CO_2 is numeric data.

57
00:04:05,295 --> 00:04:08,405
This doesn't really give us any sense of scale.

58
00:04:08,405 --> 00:04:11,420
To understand how the markers grow with emissions,

59
00:04:11,420 --> 00:04:17,270
we want to add a legend that tells us what a smaller circle really needs.

60
00:04:17,270 --> 00:04:20,840
But we have a small problem here when it comes to adding a legend.

61
00:04:20,840 --> 00:04:23,855
We only have one scatter plot, which is CO_2,

62
00:04:23,855 --> 00:04:29,050
so the legend only gives us a single dot as you see up here.

63
00:04:29,050 --> 00:04:31,415
As a workaround,

64
00:04:31,415 --> 00:04:33,325
we can actually plot

65
00:04:33,325 --> 00:04:38,720
multiple dummy scatter plot sequences so we can construct our own legend.

66
00:04:38,720 --> 00:04:42,480
Here, I'm going to plot what we saw above.

67
00:04:42,480 --> 00:04:46,210
But now, before I plot the legend,

68
00:04:46,210 --> 00:04:52,000
I am going to plot only the sizes for CO_2 at 200,

69
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:55,060
350, and 500 units.

70
00:04:55,060 --> 00:04:59,580
We're now going to loop over these.

71
00:04:59,580 --> 00:05:01,075
For each of them,

72
00:05:01,075 --> 00:05:04,070
we're going to have an empty scatter plot.

73
00:05:04,070 --> 00:05:11,550
Then it will plot those empty scatter plots on top of the original one we plotted,

74
00:05:11,550 --> 00:05:14,140
and then put the legend on top of that.

75
00:05:14,140 --> 00:05:20,980
Now we have the same plot with a meaningful legend to give us a sense of scale.

76
00:05:20,980 --> 00:05:22,650
The legend function,

77
00:05:22,650 --> 00:05:27,620
note that up until now we've only seen it with one argument,

78
00:05:27,620 --> 00:05:29,425
the labels for the plot.

79
00:05:29,425 --> 00:05:31,310
However, in this case,

80
00:05:31,310 --> 00:05:34,010
we see that the legend function takes

81
00:05:34,010 --> 00:05:37,640
two or three arguments or can take two or three arguments.

82
00:05:37,640 --> 00:05:39,535
One is the legend objects.

83
00:05:39,535 --> 00:05:43,455
The second one is the list of names.

84
00:05:43,455 --> 00:05:46,355
Finally, if we want to give it a unique title,

85
00:05:46,355 --> 00:05:48,810
we can provide that as well.

